title: For Sale:  Japanes Type 99 "Last Ditch" Arisaka
postcontent:
This was a recent acquisition of mine that I received in a trade for a different rifle. The rifle is a 27th series Type 99 made by Tokyo Juki Kogyo in late 1944 or early 1945. These are interesting rifles in that the craftsmanship compared to earlier Japanese rifles is quite a bit more rough. These "last ditch" rifles have only a simple peep sight, welded barrel bands, a wooded butt plate, no upper handguard, and very rough machining on the receiver, stock, and various metal parts.

These rifles are a great representation of the huge pressure Japan was under at the end of World War 2 due to US bombings of the mainland and lack of resources.

This rifle is a typical example of a US serviceman bring back from the end of World War 2. The Imperial mum is ground off the rifle (this was done at the end of the war, as the mum was a symbol of the Emperor) and the firing pin and safety do not match the rest of the rifle. This was probably because GI's had to make their rifle inoperable when on the ship home. Upon arriving home they collected new parts out of a bin of parts. The bolt body and extractor do match.

The bore appears unfired and is shinny with strong grooves. This rifle was probably somewhere in mainland Japan at the end of the war when the GI took it home.

I'm asking $200 for this rifle, since it's a pretty standard late war Type 99. Please don't be afraid to make me an offer. I might even trade it for different WWII era Japanese rifles or other military surplus rifles. If you'd like more photos or have any questions, please ask!

Thanks!

title: For Sale:  Tannerite Exploding Targets
postcontent:
If you have ever seen Top Shot or Sons of Guns then you've seen the exploding targets. 

Tannerite is a binary explosive used primarily as a target for firearms practice, and is unique in that it is exceptionally stable when subjected to less severe forces such as a hammer blow or being dropped. It is supplied as two powders which are combined to produce the explosive. Tannerite is a trademarked name, and binary exploding targets are a patented invention. 

Tannerite is not flammable (it is an oxygen robber and will extinguish fire). When the bullet penetrates the mixed powders, the molecules separate and cause a molecular breakdown which in turn causes a sonic boom and water vapor to appear in the air. 

Since the two components are not explosive until mixed, they can legally be purchased and used in the USA without any kind of license. 

I have 1/2 lbs and 1 lbs targets.

I acquired this a while back, but it ended up being a near clone of my Savage BAT/S in terms of accuracy. With another little one on the way, I can't justify having two SUB-MOA rifles in the same caliber. The rifle is beautiful, and very well balanced. The scope that was on it was not appropriate for the quality of rifle, so I purchased a $500+ Sightron SII 3-12x42: http://www.opticsplanet.net/sightron...siib31242.html

Beautiful English Walnut Stock
Round Top Receiver (later models were flat top)
Purchased from Gibb's Rifle Company for $2,600

These were in British service from 1972-2003

title: For Sale:  91 Toyota Land Cruiser (no title)
postcontent: I picked up this 91 as a "parts" vehicle but it was too nice to part out frankly so I've just been holding on to it a few years here and I could use the parking space in the shed.  Truck is solid with a good body, even has valet keyless system on the vehicle but no key fob.  Story goes the front differential went out on the truck, Toyota wanted LOTS to repair at the dealer, owner said forget it and left it to a friend and moved away... never got around to giving the guy the title.  I purchased it from that fella without a title, just a bill of sale, will provide bill of sale with purchase/trade so you can get a title bond on it if you end up so inclined.  Should be able to get a title bond from talking to the folks at the DMV and tag offices both, (THEY WERE HELPFUL!!) and get it on the road or this would be a PERFECT off road project!  If you go the off-road toy route you could strip the truck of many parts and help fund your build... the rear leather seats are worth a bit, and if you're going extreme and doorless you've got doors with switches, etc you could part out as well.  I priced out a front differential at like $450 for a used one if you wanted to fix things.  Transmission and Motor supposed to be in good order, wasn't cranked for a while before I got it, think the fuel pump went out while it was sitting (notorious on Toyotas that sit for a long while).  Interior would clean up good, needs front seats recovered or some seat covers or something.  Back seats (leather) and 3rd row seats look good with no tears or rips.  Tires have some decent tread but are older.  Great project truck or parts truck, TONS worth of parts here... from all the good body panels, to the leather back seats, motor, trans, rear diff, etc!  Sunroof (works) several power windows I think didn't... one or two... I tested them.  Honestly the fuel pump may be fine and I just don't know how the dern security system works... it has a power cut switch that isn't marked so I could be totally confused or missing something there.  I haven't spent much time on this thing, I've got a lot of projects right now!  Oh, and I think the windshield has a crack and the hood has a dent from a limb that hit the corner... only bad body panel I think at all.  It needs TLC to make it road worthy again, thus the low price... 180 something thousand miles... nothing bad for these motors.  Would consider partial trade on nice firearms, decent size good safe for long guns, cash, gold, or silver.
